            <fr:title text="Dense">Dense</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> of a topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is said to be dense in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> if the closure of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> equals <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is dense in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> if for every point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> and every open neighborhood <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, the intersection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \cap  U]]></fr:tex> is non-empty.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
